          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
          Israeli top spy resigns
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/ronen-bar-resignation-israel-netanyahu-intelligence-chief.png" alt="The head of Israel’s domestic intelligence service, Ronen Bar, stated that he would step down on 15 June, six weeks after Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu attempted to remove him from office" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>The head of Israel’s domestic intelligence service, Ronen Bar, stated that he would step down on 15 June, six weeks after Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu attempted to dismiss him from office. Credits: Daily Post</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Israel’s domestic intelligence chief, Ronen Bar, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-h1-1-announced-his-resignation" target="_blank">announced his resignation</a>, effective June 15. He stepped down due to Shin Bet's (one of three principal organizations of the Israeli Intelligence Community) failure to warn about the October 7, 2023, Hamas attack, which killed over 1,200 Israelis and sparked the Gaza war.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          He stated, “All systems collapsed that night” and called for accountability from those responsible.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Bar's resignation follows PM Benjamin Netanyahu's attempt to dismiss him last month over a “crisis of confidence” surrounding the attack. It led to judicial challenges and was halted by Israel’s Supreme Court. 
         </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Last week, Bar alleged that Netanyahu had tried to fire him for refusing to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-h1-2-pledge-his-loyalty" target="_blank">pledge his loyalty</a> to the PM over the courts and tried to use the agency to spy on anti-government protesters. Netanyahu, in his response, rejected Bar’s accusations. He repeatedly referred to a “deep state” in Israel that he alleges seeks to thwart democratically elected leaders and undermine elected governments.
         </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Critics warn that Bar's departure may enable Netanyahu to appoint a loyalist to head the Shin Bet. Bar joins the former defense minister and army chief on the list of senior security officials who have left since October 7. 
         </p>
        
        </mj-text>
