          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">India looking pretty</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent stated that the first trading agreement will likely be awarded to India.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent stated that many top trading partners have submitted “very good” proposals to escape upcoming US tariffs. He announced that the first agreement <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-h3-5-could-be-with-india" target="_blank">could be with India</a>, possibly this week or next. After morning TV interviews, Bessent stated that Trump will be “intimately involved” in each agreement with about 15 to 18 key partners. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          He mentioned ongoing talks with Japan and South Korea. However, South Korea’s government said it cannot finalize an agreement before its presidential election on May 9. Japan’s election in July could also complicate discussions. Some expect an announcement at June’s G7 summit in Canada.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Trump’s sweeping tariffs are on hold until July 8. China has begun exempting some US products from its retaliatory duties, indicating a desire to de-escalate tensions.  Bessent said it’s up to Beijing to restart negotiations.</p>
        </mj-text>
