        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇮🇳 Kashmir attack unites political foes in both Pakistan and India</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Following the deadly attack in Indian Kashmir, both India and Pakistan have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-br1-6-exchanged-fire" target="_blank">exchanged fire</a> along the Line of Control, expelled diplomats, and shut the border. However, it has united people on the domestic front. In India, opposition leaders like Rahul Gandhi and Asaduddin Owaisi united to support PM Modi’s voice for unity. They warned that terrorists aim to “pit brother against brother.” Indian Youth Congress rallies showed flags and called for strong retaliation. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          In Pakistan, major parties and the military blamed India for “orchestrating” the attack. The Senate passed an anti-India resolution unanimously after Imran Khan’s Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) party voted in favor to prevent appearing unpatriotic. Analysts warn that both governments face pressure to show strength. This could risk further escalation in the disputed Himalayan region.</p>
        </mj-text>
