        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇲🇹 The EU court rejects Malta’s golden passport scheme</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Malta’s “golden passport” scheme, which granted EU citizenship in exchange for capital of at least €700,000, has been ruled unlawful by the EU Court of Justice. The European Commission argued that the program violated Malta’s duty of sincere cooperation and reduced EU citizenship to a mere commodity. The court agreed, emphasizing that the scheme did not require actual residence in Malta. It also ordered Malta to cover the judicial expenses.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Malta’s program was the last remaining <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-30-04-2025-br2-7-eu-citizenship-by-investment-scheme" target="_blank">EU citizenship by investment scheme</a>. Cyprus ended its program in 2020, followed by Bulgaria in 2022. However, some EU countries still provide “golden visas” that provide residency in exchange for investment.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Critics warn that such schemes can facilitate currency laundering and sanctions evasion, particularly in the wake of Russia’s 2022 invasion of Ukraine. The Commission firmly stated that European citizenship is not for lease. Malta has announced it will revise its citizenship rules to comply with the ruling, although previously granted citizenships will remain valid.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
